    <item>
      <title>Summit II Plans: Issue 2: The Secondary Role.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=7811#M7811</link>
      <description>Summit Plans: Issue II: The Secondary Role. Soloing clerics, stackability, low healing situations&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Other classes now are (rightfully so) gaining improved healing abilities. Already a group has a choice of Clerics and Druids and sometimes even Shaman and Paladin's as their main healer. Cleric healing is very powerful, but increasingly cleric healing is almost TOO powerful for normal grouping situations.  Why would a group leader look for a cleric who is basically overhealing with every heal (not because the cleric wants to; their heals are just that strong) when they can get any one of any other adequat ehealing classes who can do other things. It is time for clerics to have a strong, viable secondary role in groups. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Whether it is in a group that does not need heavy healing, a group that has doubled up on the clerics for whatever reason, or the soloing cleric, the cleric does not have much more to bring to the table beside their healing power. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As things stand right now, the soloing cleric can get eaten up by low blues in old content, which we should ideally we should be able to get through.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;And in groups that don't need the strong healing power that the cleric brings, a group leader can compare us to the other healing classes and decide to go with a druid, or a paladin or a shaman because all three can bring other things to the group beyond the healing a cleric has.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;And in groups with two clerics, there is a strong mindset that the second cleric is just a hanger on who isn't bringing much to the group. There is a strong feeling that the group is humouring the two clerics by pairing them up.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;We do not want, nor need the ability to tank mobs (other than in extreme group wipings anyways situations). What we do need is a valid secondary ability, most likely as a semi-solid DPS class of some sort, that we can bring out to the group and not be embarassed about.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Proposed Solutions:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;1. Cleric stances. Similar to druid stances that are in the works, give us something similar. Let us go into a battle stance that will turn off a cleric's natural healing bonus, but increase our spell damage and meelee damage.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;2. Give us another spell line that does not check against MR. Our retribution line is great, except for the fact that mob Magic Resist is so high nowadays the spell resists like crazy. A new nuke spell line, added in the higher levels when resists become most noticable (probably around L45+) that is chromatic on its resist checks. To reflect its higher chances of landing, have it do slightly less damage. Another option would be to shift the higher end nukes (Down to and including Judgment) from an MR check to a Chromatic check.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;3. Recently, the game has been shifting to put meelee in as a cleric's secondary role. With that in mind, it is high time our meelee skills reflected that. We should be close to the Paladin's if not identical at the higher levels. We do NOT need the extra attack skills like "Double Attack" and stuff, but we should be making decent DPS with our meelee skills none the less. Capping a cleric's offensive skills near a level-equivalent Paladin's level would help solidify a Cleric's meelee abilities.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;4. It used to be that root was a viable tactic to stop a mob from running and to root park. Cleric roots however are proving to be inadequate in the 60+ game. Between our DoN Ward spell and our hammer procs, stopping a mob from running becomes chain casting root. We need our root spell strengthened so it can endure through more than 1 or 2 procs/nukes. If the DoN ward is spread down to the lower levels this will become a problem down there as well.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;5. An improved root system would help with runners, but there is another suggestion that could work well for soloing clerics/clerics (and a similar version for paladin's) fighting in groups without a snarer. Create a new "Infuriate" spell line that when landed will infuriate the mob, keep the mob focused on the group, unsnare and unslow the mob, but keep the mob from running.</description>
