    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit II Plans: Issue 2: The Secondary Role.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=9488#M9488</link>
      <description>I understand and agree with the feelings about Complete Heal. It is a game mechanic that is slowly on its way out and is unlikely to see any upgrades ever. (not impossible but very unlikely).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The problem with Complete heal is, you push one button, and you can not do anything else for 10 seconds. You can't move, you can't DPS, you can't alternate heal, you can't cure, you can't use an AA, you can't nuke, you can't stun, without interrupting that CHeal. It makes clerics a very monotonous class if that's all you see them as. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Quite frankly, we as clerics have been spoiled by Cheal for 9 expansions now, and because of that many are unwilling to look beyond that.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Luckily (depending on your PoV) the Dev's are shaking things up slowly. They are making encounters that make CHeal virtually impossible to use. Either damage spikes too much, the mob stuns too much, silences, the AE's are too high forcing you to heal your group with other tools, the mob shadowsteps or grav fluxes, mob casts diseases and curses that have to be cured fast, etc.... Most of those appeared in raid encounters but they are slowly trickling down to the group encounters too.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The CHeal playstyle is still around and will be around for a long while yet, but other playstyles are coming back too (or new ones developing). The Vie + regen cleric, the stunning cleric (need more work there to get the stuns back in line) and yes even the nuking cleric and the meeleeing cleric.</description>
