    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit II Plans: Issue 2: The Secondary Role.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8982#M8982</link>
      <description>Hi guys, druid stopping in, hope you don't mind.  :)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Whaxx wrote:&lt;br&gt;Add slow, track, and DoT in there, and you got......  a Druid.&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;Uh no . . druids have never gotten slow.  The closest thing we ever got was an attack debuff, and while that was good for a 10-15% dmg decrease back in PoP (it's mostly useless for that purpose now), even then it still wasn't anywhere close to slow.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;For the people afraid of druids, I'll reassure you that even as druid healing increases, you've still got a pretty tight grasp on a group slot as long as we don't have XP rezzes, especially in long grind type groups.  And that's without any secondary role.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;When I started playing my druid, I was informed that druids were wisdom casters, also known as priests.  And as a priest I would be able to heal.  I fully expected that clerics would have other tricks: bigger heals, faster heals, heal over time spells, group heals; there are plenty of examples of that.  But I also fully expected to be a functional healer.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;If I need FT20 and 45% healing focus to heal where a cleric needs FT10 and 30% healing focus I have no problem with that at all.  I expected clerics to be ahead, and clerics to be able to heal specific encounters sooner.  But I still expected to be able to do it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;And I am pleased that it definitely looks like the game is headed in that direction.  I will need to spend more time earning AAs or gearing up, but I will work as a healer.  And honestly, I think the overhealing argument is a pretty minor one.  When I am working as healer in non-trivial content I really don't have time or mana to nuke and I really prefer not to snare, since I will inevitably get caught at some point healing when I need to be snaring.  In trivial content I am preferable, but since the content is trivial so is the benefit.  Additionally, if the content is trivial and little/no healing is required, there are other classes more desirable than a druid for that slot.  FAR more often, the cleric will be chosen for the DVA/rez safety than the druid for a little extra dps.  (It's worth pointing out that druid dps is correctly located below wizard dps, and since wizard dps is currently pathetic, druid dps is abysmal.  Honestly the secondary dps advantage may be totally due to perception.  When I am serving as healer, my only real damage contribution is DS, which usually runs around 10-20dps, depending on various factors.  So actually a meleeing cleric serving as healer may well add more damage than a druid.)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;However the stackability is a serious issue.  But stackability is also where the secondary role question is absolutely unavoidable.  If there are two clerics in a group, one of them is not healing.  (Not unless it's a really unusual group.)  With two druids, one of them can focus on snare/FR debuff/nuking.  Druid dps is a joke right now, but if and when caster dps gets fixed it could be at least worthwhile, if not good.  For the second cleric in a group, what do you do?  People like Boradek who oppose ancillary skills and secondary roles . . do you think that two clerics should never group together?  Because that's the situation you're supporting, even if inadvertently.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I would have no problem with a cleric doing 100-150dps meleeing solo.  With my DoTs when I am soloing I do 200-250dps depending on crits, and that's with tacvi/anguish foci.  That's not sustainable indefinitely for me, but I imagine the cleric would have to heal himself and eventually med also.  I also have no problem with a second cleric doing that same 100-150dps melee in a group, as long as it is the second cleric.  Doing that while healing would be overpowered I think, but if you get in some battle cleric stance, or cast some super melee buff with a hefty mana drain component (in the neighborhood of 50-70, basically enough to negate modern mana regen) in order to do that damage it sounds good to me.  Incidentally, in a group setting with little downtime I currently sustain in the neighborhood of 100dps nuking.  That's just all I can do with max FT etc.</description>
